  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (US) introduced initial reporting requirements\n- First focused on financial transparency and suspicious transaction reporting\n\n2. International Developments\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created international standards and recommendations for combating money laundering\n- Developed comprehensive global guidelines\n\n3. Key Legislation Milestones\n- 1990s: Enhanced regulatory frameworks\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded AML requirements\n- Increased reporting obligations and criminal penalties\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Expanded regulations to cover digital currencies\n- Added cryptocurrency transaction monitoring requirements\n- Enhanced digital transaction tracking mechanisms\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased focus on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- More comprehensive risk-based approaches\n- Greater international cooperation\n\n6. Emerging Challenges\n- Addressing complex digital financial ecosystems\n- Combating sophisticated money laundering techniques\n- Balancing privacy concerns with regulatory requirements\n\nThe legislative landscape continues evolving to address emerging financial crime risks.",
